article.headline: Washington snaps three-game slide
article.linkText: Beard hits first eight FGs, scores 23 in Mystics win
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rookie Alana Beard cooled off the hottest team
in the WNBA.

"I guess the fire's out," Beard said after scoring 23 points,
including two free throws with 1:11 remaining, to lead the
Washington Mystics to a 65-61 victory Friday night over Minnesota,
ending the Lynx's six-game winning streak.

Beard, who made her first eight shots, finished 8-for-9 from the
field and 7-for-7 at the free-throw line as the Mystics snapped a
three-game losing streak.

Katie Smith, who led the Lynx with 19 points, left with 11:09
remaining in the game when she injured her right knee while
scrambling with Beard for a loose ball.

"I just went after a loose ball and kind of hyperextended my
knee," Smith said. "God, I hope it's not anything serious, but
who knows? It hurts; obviously I would've been back in the game if
it didn't."

With Smith on the bench, the Lynx managed only eight points the
rest of the game.

"Usually, when you're down by three and you're Minnesota, you
know you're getting the ball in Katie Smith's hands, and she wasn't
out there," Beard said. "No one was out there, really, to get the
ball to."

Smith, averaging 24.2 points in her previous five games, made
five of her first seven shots and scored 13 points to lead the Lynx
to a 36-34 halftime lead. She entered the game as the league's
third-leading scorer averaging 18.8 points.

Teresa Edwards' turnover with 7.1 seconds remaining cost the
Lynx their final shot at a tie. Muriel Page's free throw with 6
seconds left sealed the victory.

Chasity Melvin finished with 11 points and seven rebounds for
Washington.

"The last time down, I just said, 'I'm going to go through them
and try to get a foul or put the shot down,' " Melvin said of her
layup that gave the Mystics a 62-61 lead with 1:50 left. "I think
that really gave us a lift. Then we got back on defense and that's
really what won the game."

Chamique Holdsclaw, the league's second-leading scorer averaging
19.8 points, finished with nine points on 3-for-17 shooting and
four rebounds.

Nakia Sanford grabbed a career-high eight rebounds for the
Mystics.

Nicole Ohlde finished with 15 points and six rebounds for the
Lynx.

Beard's three-point play gave the Mystics a 45-44 lead with 14
minutes remaining. Ohlde responded with two free throws and a layup
on the run to give the Lynx a 48-45 lead. Beard's driving layup
tied it at 56 with 7:37 left.

Beard shot 6-for-6 in the first half to lead Washington. The
rest of the Mystics shot a combined 22 percent in the half.

"In the first half we took an unbelievable amount of jump shots
instead of attacking the basket," Beard said.
